column3:
My office building advices to have three days worth of food at out desks in 
case of a natural disaster, but they also have rations on hand in case. I'm 
vegan and the likelihood of them having something for me is slim, so I 
decided to get silent after this review. I tried a bottle and shared it 
with my coworkers to get their take. I thought it takes like thin pancake 
batter, others thought there was a hint of banana. All in all it was pretty 
decent and it's there in a pinch. One day I had to run to an after school 
event with my son and I knew I wouldn't be able to grab dinner, so this was 
a nice in an emergency food source. The price point is definitely high but 
if it's "in case of..." It works nicely.﻿

column3:
Pretty sad that people are angry at you because you are Vegan. It is a 
fantastic choice, those who eat meat are statistically known to live 10 
years or more shorter lives (And Vegans have a 45% lower chance to have a 
heart attack). I have been Vegetarian most of my life, I eat delicious food 
all the time here in California, I guess most people don't notice 
Vegetarian food is available in nearly every store. When you head to 
Walmart look in the frozen sections for the vast amount of Vegetarian 
burger patties, chicken nuggets, bacon, sea food, and more. I suppose 
restaurants depend more on location, a friend of mine who used to love 
meat, turned Vegetarian a couple years back. He lives in New York, so there 
aren't that many vegan/vegetarian restaurants. However, in California I can 
eat a delicious vegan west-style BBQ bacon burger with a side of seasoned 
fries within 7 minutes of my location.

Like others pointed out, YouTube is about the creators uploading whatever 
they want. If you don't like it, no one is forcing you to watch it, simply 
exit out. If anything this will help cleanse the community, those of you 
who are raging, unsubscribe, by doing so you are helping to get rid of the 
cancer of his community.﻿

column3:
The side effect you described is probably from not chewing. Not chewing 
your food will get your glycemic index out of whack as well as not regulate 
your insulin levels. I had this problem with soylent. Chew a stick of gum 
for 15 minutes before you drink soylent and you won't feel so spaced out 
and skippy. Not chewing will also jack up your blood pressure to unhealthy 
levels even though your not getting too much sodium. This is experience 
talking. Been having this at least 2 meals a day for over 2 months checking 
blood pressure and weight by the week.﻿

column3:
Looks like the seeds in Jake are flaxseeds. The use of while seeds worries 
me. There's a high chance your body won't be getting anything from the 
seeds at all, because flaxseed needs to be ground for your body to be able 
to digest it. This means if you live on Jake alone you will most definitely 
start to see signs of malnutrition, as you won't be getting your fats. The 
use of ground flaxseed in Joylent, rather than flaxseed oil (like in 
Queal), is also interesting. I was under the impression that ground 
flaxseed needs to be refrigerated in order to not go rancid. I wonder why 
this doesn't seem to apply to meal replacement mixes.﻿
column8: Review: Queal vs Jake vs Joylent

column3:
Joylent all the way for me (Vanilla) ! I've tried queal and I didn't like 
it that much because the powder just didn't dissolve that easy, it felt to 
me like a mix of water and thick lumps of powder. On the contrary, Joylent 
dissolves very easily after a couple of shakes, giving it a very smooth and 
creamy texture that is just very enjoyable to drink. I haven't tried Jake 
yet, but after watching this review I probably never will. Also because I'm 
so content with Joylent. I also really like the philosophy behind the 
company.
Great review btw :)﻿

column8: Joylent vs Aussielent Review

column3:
Haha, I hope at 2:09 you didn't intend to say "milligrams" =P
Good review; cheers. I've only tried Aussielent Vanilla, but have been 
having it happily for breakfast and lunch (1/3 packet per meal) for about 
three months now. I prefer it quite a bit thicker than you - perhaps 2:1 
powder to water. I've found a Nutribullet mixes it really well and the two 
pieces are easy to rinse after and then hand-wash in the evening.
It's strange though, how the taste changes when it's pre-mixed. When left 
to go bad, it releases gas, smells bad, and tastes sour. It tends to head 
in this direction rather quickly; even when leaving it sealed in the fridge 
in the morning, it starts to taste a little funny by the evening. I tend to 
mix breakfast and lunch in the morning, and leave the latter portion in my 
bag until lunch, which works out fine.﻿

I train everyday run 10k 3 x a week and weight train with cardio to finish

Rubbish review - agree with the other negative comments. \xa3225 pw? Mad. 
Also, the all or nothing approach is crazy. I'm trying (quite pleasant 
tasting) Huel as partial meal replacement for particular health reasons, 
and finding it fine so far. About \xa31.60 per meal. Would I replace all 
meals? Nope, that'd be unbearable. Is it a healthy, easy and reasonably 
priced replacement for one or two meals a day? Yep. Will I take it with me 
on long travels to ensure easy, healthy nutrition when I'm miles from food 
I can tolerate? Reckon that'd be about perfect. Just add clean water from 
my water to go and shake. I just hope border guards don't confuse the white 
Huel powder with illicit substances....﻿

column3:
Looks like the seeds in Jake are flaxseeds. The use of while seeds worries 
me. There's a high chance your body won't be getting anything from the 
seeds at all, because flaxseed needs to be ground for your body to be able 
to digest it. This means if you live on Jake alone you will most definitely 
start to see signs of malnutrition, as you won't be getting your fats. The 
use of ground flaxseed in Joylent, rather than flaxseed oil (like in 
Queal), is also interesting. I was under the impression that ground 
flaxseed needs to be refrigerated in order to not go rancid. I wonder why 
this doesn't seem to apply to meal replacement mixes.﻿
column8: Review: Queal vs Jake vs Joylent

column3:
Joylent all the way for me (Vanilla) ! I've tried queal and I didn't like 
it that much because the powder just didn't dissolve that easy, it felt to 
me like a mix of water and thick lumps of powder. On the contrary, Joylent 
dissolves very easily after a couple of shakes, giving it a very smooth and 
creamy texture that is just very enjoyable to drink. I haven't tried Jake 
yet, but after watching this review I probably never will. Also because I'm 
so content with Joylent. I also really like the philosophy behind the 
company.
Great review btw :)﻿

column3:
Hey been using Queal for 1.5 year now, I make it a little different i start 
with around 200 ml water then add the queal.

Then i close up the bottle and fill it with another 200 ml water this way 
the water is on both sides of the queal.

Then i shake it up.

The good thing about water on both sides is that there is less queal 
sticking to the top of the bottle making clearing easier and wasted even 
less.

Tip: add water 250ml add queal 150 , add a 150ml milk like soya or almond 
and you have a very nice milkshake.

Enjoy life enjoy Queal﻿

column3:
I using Jake Light since a couple of weeks and I like it a lot. How it 
tastes is a bit difficult. Like it says on the package "vanilla". The first 
time I used I can not say it tasted great. But certainly not bad. After a 
while using it ... it is better then the first time. It is not dessert, it 
is food. And it is fine. 

When you make the shake there is no need to do it like in the video. Just 
fill the cup up to the 400ml mark. Open a bag wide and put the top of the 
bag in to the top of the cup . Gently beat the the bag while you turn 
around the cup. All of the powder goes in of the cup. 

If you like it very liquid drink it directly. If you leave it 5 minutes or 
so it is more thick. Still very drinkable but not so runny. 

A good point is that the cup is very easy to clean. The Jake food washes 
away very easy, also if you do not wash it directly after use.

If you compare the price of Jake with other similar products look very good 
at the real price per kcal. The definition of what "a meal" is can vary. 
And the price per meal is what is advertised. 

Jake is easy to use and stays good for a year. I use it mostly because this 
way I know exactly how many calories I eat, what is important when you try 
to limited your intake.﻿

column3:
Good review on these things.  Did you get it on offer?  Checking on the 
Jake and Joylent websites tonight, Jake seems to be quite a bit more 
expensive than Joylent.
Jake original: €64.00+free shipping for 20 meals / €3.20 per meal.
Jake light: €59.00+free shipping for 20 meal / €2.95 per meal.
Joylent: €30+€5 shipping for 15 meals / €2.33 per meal.
I'm looking to try one of these shakes, but when is someone going to use 
something instead of the artificial sweetener sucralose (E955) in these 
powders? It seems that Soylent, Joylent and Jake all contain this. I can't 
stomach that stuff. I would prefer to add my own choice of sweetener 
afterwards (if at all).  Looking on the ingredients Jake has dextrose 
(D-Glucose) in it already, so why add an artificial sweetener too?  They 
should include a sachet of sweetener if they must include it then the 
customer could adjust to their own personal tastes and preferences.﻿

column3:
Looks like the seeds in Jake are flaxseeds. The use of while seeds worries 
me. There's a high chance your body won't be getting anything from the 
seeds at all, because flaxseed needs to be ground for your body to be able 
to digest it. This means if you live on Jake alone you will most definitely 
start to see signs of malnutrition, as you won't be getting your fats. The 
use of ground flaxseed in Joylent, rather than flaxseed oil (like in 
Queal), is also interesting. I was under the impression that ground 
flaxseed needs to be refrigerated in order to not go rancid. I wonder why 
this doesn't seem to apply to meal replacement mixes.﻿

dissolves very easily after a couple of shakes, giving it a very smooth and 
creamy texture that is just very enjoyable to drink. I haven't tried Jake 
yet, but after watching this review I probably never will. Also because I'm 
so content with Joylent. I also really like the philosophy behind the 
company.
Great review btw :)﻿

column3:
We have very similar problems with our diet. My experience was far 
different though. I drink a shake for breakfast, then one for lunch, and 
then I eat a regular sensible supper. Sometimes I have a snack of a banana 
or apple in the afternoon. I always use milk to mix it it just taste 
better. You got to have a wire ball inside your shaker to mix it up and 
when you do shake it you need to shake it for about three minutes I know it 
sounds like a long time but consider it part of the workout. When I got 
tired of doing that I just made two in the blender and I drink one and then 
I save the other one for lunch put it in my lunchbox on ice.that feeling of 
being hungry is a good feeling if you want to lose weight you'll have to 
get used to it. The good thing about Lean one is that the calories it gives 
you are good, easily burnable calories. This is by far the best meal 
supplement I have ever experienced﻿

column3:
I can tolerate taste, it's just important to me that my meal replacement 
supplement is as close to the natural state of food as possible, and the 
only company that does that right now is GOL (although there's a higher 
ratio of sprouts to greens with their meal replacement). 

I would also, heavily, not recommend that you mix these with water - better 
if you can, obviously, but just mixing it with a non-dairy beverage gets 
the trick done.

Take it from a 26-year-old male who gets mistaken for an 18-year-old - 
these replacement meals (only vegan and whole food based) will provide you 
with the highest amounts of antioxidants.

﻿

have to order the vegetarian menu, but just omit putting the pat of butter 
in your food that they put on the tray. I would take the soylent to have as 
an addition to the small side dishes they'll be sending to you, just ask 
for extra equal to put in it and shake it up to make it sweet. Hopefully 
they will be nice and accommodating of your vegan diet.﻿

column3:
Hi Michelle! You ABSOLUTELY CAN eat large significant calorie meals of 
fruit/ smoothies BUT only if you say bye-bye to the high density carbs such 
as rice etc. Each of the three major leap-levels of physical performance 
and health, in relation to significant fuel modifications to the diet 
require a transition period. Those who eat rice, for example, AND eat large 
amounts of fruit/ smoothies are going to have problems. The high density 
carbs act like fats in interfering with digestion, assimilation and blood 
sugar efficiency. Eating rice for dinner and then having a fruit smoothie 
for breakfast is a bad mix, as those who "want their cake and eat it too" 
will surely discover. There are other metabolic-affecting factors such as 
time on diet, intensity of regular activity, etc., but suffice it to say 
that you can't mix low density carbs with high density carbs as a 
significant fuel source and expect even marginal health or performance.﻿

column3:
My opinion is to use supplements for short periods of time, for a 
specifically selected goal, and not as total replacement of meals. Making 
your own shakes out of normal food is probably less risky than processed 
ones, though. 

1) Almost everyone who isn't going hungry, elderly, or disabled in the US 
has adequate minimum nutrition, even if the PROPORTIONs of nutrients are 
skewed to carbs and fats. A multivitamin is usually enough, if an 
individual is concerned about missing a mineral or something in their diet.

2) Meal supplements are not replacements. Even the well known product 
Ensure that is used in many hospitals is intended to be a supplement, or a 
limited-time replacement. This is because we don't have the technology to 
exactly replicate everything from natural food.

3) Manufactured supplements are not well regulated or certified. The FDA is 
not required to check every dietary supplement unless the manufacturer 
makes a specific health claim. Sometimes consumer advocates test the 
supplements and find that the ingredients label is inaccurate. The 
manufacturing process also sometimes concentrates naturally occurring 
toxins, such as the arsenic and cadmium in whey protein that is marketed to 
athletes.﻿

column3:
So many comments saying it works and some saying it's a scam. Others saying 
"ugh" just another coach". First of all, a beachbody coach is someone who's 
used beachbody products and because they get results using their products 
they share what they're doing with people who they think can benefit from 
it. That's all they are. Now there is a business opportunity and there are 
some people who treat it like a pure sales business but the truth is it's 
just people sharing what worked for them. As for shakeology, the shake for 
me i've felt a difference one month using it and one month without it. 
HOWEVER it's up to the buyer if they want to get the shake or not. If you 
do a workout program you don't need the shake to get results but it can add 
to your results if you take it. The price may seem a little high but it 
balances out to about $4-5 per serving. If you can replicate the 
ingredients in the shake great! There is no single path to following a 
healthy lifestyle there are simply different ways to get different results. 
if some of you think it's a scam. If you believe you can create a different 
shake or suppliment that can help others at a cheaper price then do it! 
it's about helping people lead healthier fulfilling lives. It shouldn't be 
a competition with "hey what I do is better than what you do" If you don't 
want the shake don't get it. If you do want to try it my advice is to go by 
your opinion with how you feel it has a bottom of the bag money back 
guarantee meaning if you take the entire month of shakeology and still 
don't like it mail it back! no problem but don't attack and label EVERY 
Beachbody coach as some sort of scamming, selfish salesman because there 
are people who've gotten great results through Beachbody and want to share 
the secret of their success with those who struggle with the same 
situations they've recovered from. If you believe you can create something 
more then do it. It shouldn't be a "i'm right you're wrong debate" it 
should be for the people.﻿

column3:
I think Tony Horton makes BeachBody for me.  His personality and face are 
just so iconic that he is more than just P90X or Shakeology to me.

My favorite benefit of Shakeology is that it helps curb my cravings.  I 
actually feel full during lunch (when I take it) and it prevents me from 
munching on snacks.  I used to snack all the time around lunch.  

My favorite flavor is definitely Chocolate.  It just tastes way better than 
I imagined—and this is coming from someone who used to eat boxes of Godiva 
truffles every month LOL (ah, I miss making money lol).  I mix it with PB2 
to make a Reese’s flavored shake—my all-time favorite combination.

The most important benefits to me are:
1. Price: At only $4 a serving it is cheaper than eating out.  I used to 
eat out A LOT as a Yelp Elite member.
2. Curbs Cravings: I no longer get tempted to snack and go over my calorie 
limits.  I didn’t actually think Shakeology could help with that, but it 
has.  I’m not questioning it anymore haha.

not even lying or exaggerating.  I used to review decent restaurants in

column3:
I hate how when people praise Shakeology for its ingredients, easy of 
preparation (or lack thereof), and benefits, they feel the need to have to 
say "I'm not a Beachbody coach and do not sell Shakeology."  People need to 
realize this shake isn't being touted by BB or any coach that it's an 
all-in-one "get slim fast" no-lifestyle-change kind of "miracle" 
weight-loss cure.  It's a shame because there are MANY MANY people out 
there, including myself, that are simply customers and love how Shakeology 
helps with their weight-loss/fitness journeys.  This shake is meant to be 
paired with exercise.  I'll put it to you in the simplest terms I know:  
Through its whole/super food contents, Shakeology is designed to help 
AMPLIFY your fitness results.  Take the shake while in a workout regimen, 
and you'll see that you lose THAT MUCH MORE weight, or that you gained THAT 
MUCH MORE muscle definition, or that you've achieved THAT MUCH MORE 
endurance.  It helps you get THE BEST results.﻿

salad is like $10. Just think, $10 dollars for only a salad and the shake 
is equivalent to $4 a day. Plus, I cannot imagine my girlfriend eating that 
many fruits and veggies in a day without throwing up. I think Im gonna try 
it and probably get Vanilla since Im not a chocolate person. Bottomline, I 
think the shake is great but if people took time to look at the 
ingredients, they would see its not a protein shake. The shake is mean't to 
replace a meal. I would suggest people try a sample.﻿

column3:
I don't use or distribute Herbalife products. That said this video clip was 
a hack job not worthy of being called journalism. And those of you who 
dismiss a product or a company because of the way they choose to bring 
their products to market should probably rethink that mind set. Companies 
like Herbalife and Youngevity and MANY others are helping people understand 
that if you give your body the vitamins, minerals, amino acids and the 
essential fatty acids it needs to THRIVE not just survive, you will be 
healthier, stronger and all the systems of your body will function better. 
Hence you will be less prone to illnesses and disease. The human body was 
designed with the ablity to heal istelf - as long as you 1) don't poison 
it, and, 2) give it the nuetients it needs to function optimally. 
I heard on the news recently that now 50% of Americans will have some form 
of cancer in their lifetime. If your young you may just accept that or 
think... well I'll deal with that when the time comes. Well, when that time 
comes you'd better hope these companies and others like them are still 
around. Otherwise your only option is going to be to go see a doctor who 
will perscribe some drugs designed tol mask or manage the symptoms you 
have. Our "health-care" system isn't treating or even looking for the "root 
cause" of patient's problems. In other words they are not interested in 
curing you and I don't see that changing anytime soon. If you are young 
you'd be wise to start learing about nutrition now and start learning not 
to eat with your eyes. Learn and train yourself to eat with your brain, and 
not your eyes. We, Americans, are killing ourselves out of ignorace about 
what and how to eat, what food has nutricianal value and which "FOODS" 
don't and our children are suffering BIG TIME because of it. 
Just becuse a peice of video was produced and aired by ABC, NBC, etc 
doesn't mean its correct. Likewise just becuase product is distributed by a 
company like Youngevity, or Herbalife instead of Walmart or Amazon, doesn't 
mean it's not good - it doesn't mean that it is either. So, YOU are going 
to have to learn to determin what's good and what's not good for yourself. 
Don't realy on your government (FDA) to do it for you, AND it's not their 
place to regulate the industry for you either. We probaly wouldn't trust it 
if they did. Food lables have helped a lot but you still have to have some 
basic knowledge that we should be teaching in schools and maybe some 
schools are starting too. I hope so. It's kind of important stuff. 
I will say though that the cultures of some of those MLM companies makes 
their motivation for selling these kinds of products suspect. Many of the 
distributs do make false or imbelished claims so It's definately "buyer 
beware" and that's all the more reason to get educted. You really can help 
your body Thrive and become less prone to a bunch of diseases. Live Longer, 
Stronger and Wiser. Then take that knowledge and help others!﻿

column3:
Congrats on your weight loss. I really love the concept of a truly plant 
based vegan diet. It is so good for the body, good for the environment and 
something I am currently striving for. I would just like to say, I think 
you looked beautiful before, just as you look beautiful after. I think that 
the concept of losing weight for health and for beauty need to be 
separated. We must be inclusive of all body types and people because 
honestly, you really didnt look "fat" before. Watching you call yourself 
disgusting I think is hurtful to yourself as well as anyone else watching 
that may be that size or perhaps even larger. Also, the correlation between 
"size zero and perfect" is also in my opinion, misleading. If you are happy 
where you are, that is perfect. I hope no one perceives a size six, or size 
16 for that matter as imperfect. A person of any size is valuable, 
beautiful, and perfect the way they are. If they choose to be healthy and 
loose weight, that awesome, but they are certainly not disgusting for being 
what society deems as overweight. I love everything else and dont mean to 
criticize, but as a plus size woman, just recently joining the quest to 
loose weight in a healthy, plant based way, I feel it is important that 
women accept and love themselves no matter what. I love my body and am not 
ashamed of it. I merely want to extend my health and longevity as much as 
possible and feel more energetic during my life. Thank you for this video 
:)﻿

one on Dr Bernstein 80 pounds 4 months.
Problem is I gained it all back and then some as soon as I started eating 
normal food.
When I decided to lose weight this time all I did was the simplest thing 
quit pop and junk food!! Very important to get off that shit!! At supper 
rather than fill up a dinner plate I used the next size of plate down!! I 
continued this at each of my meals.
I still ate what everybody else ate.
When I was finished and if I was still hungry I waited 20 minutes from when 
I finished eating and if I was still hungry I would have a little more. 
Honestly I rarely had more because i was comfortable.
If there was dessert like pie which I love I would just take half of 
whatever I used to. 
Never once stopped me from losing weight that week.
I stuck to this simple plan for a year. I chose to quit salt and drink 6 to 
8 bottles 500 ml water a day 
Ive kept the weight off for over a year and I feel a heck of a lot better 
and people look at me differently which is always good.
please remember I did this for me no else. I wanted to do what ever I could 
see my kids grow up and their kids.
After 3 months of no salt I went to Wendy's and got a classic single 
burger. I was so looking forward go that burger and it was a treat for me.
My mouth was watering and I took a bite and was shocked at the amount of 
salt in that burger.
It was like someone had put the whole thing of salt in that burger.
Well its been almost two years and I've never ordered a fast food burger 
since.
It's all about COMMITMENT and DETERMINATION which you seem to have both.
Congratulations on your significant weight loss you should be very proud of 
yourself!!﻿

column3:
Fats, oils, and butters aren't what make meals unhealthy. Fat is good for 
you, in moderation, just like anything else. Most people's worst offense is 
overeating in general, especially carbs (bread, rice, pasta being the big 
3). All carbs break down into sugar, and sugar will definitely make you 
gain weight. The idea that "fat is unhealthy" is unfortunately a very old 
and antique way of thinking that just won't seem to die. That being said, 
that slimfast diet seems super gimmicky. Of course people might see results 
after 7 days of undereating, but it doesn't seem very nutritious.
Cheers!﻿

themselves a horrible reputation for awful customer service. See Yelp where 
they have a two star review, mostly for ILLEGALLY renewing consumer 
subscriptions without their knowledge or consent. They have an F rating 
with the BBB for ignoring consumer complaints. Try Love with Food. They are 
much more reasonably priced, and a very honest company.﻿

column3:
This company has the worst customer service ever.

I just moved and I changed my address on the website the only place you can 
change it. I get the tracking info for my August boxes, I'm subscribed to 
three boxes, and I check to see where my boxes are. Tracking info says 
they've been delivered, they shipped them to the old address though.

Obviously I'm pretty disappointed so I email them letting them know what 
happened. They respond saying that I should have emailed them to change my 
shipping address and that if I want my August boxes I will have to pay $6 
more per box for them to be shipped to the correct address, the address 
that I had already changed on their website which says NOTHING anywhere as 
far as having to email them to change your shipping location. 

I let them know that I thought it was pretty messed up how they were 
handling this situation considering it was their error and their website 
issues that caused it to happen. To which they let me know that they would 
be adding a note to their website to email them if you need to change your 
shipping address. Yet are still requiring that I pay them another $18 on 
top of the already $70+ that I paid for my August boxes. 

Now they've stopped responding to me and are censoring me from their 
Facebook page. 

This is a terrible company with terrible standards, they will not last 
long.﻿

column3:
This company has the worst customer service ever.

I just moved and I changed my address on the website the only place you can 
change it. I get the tracking info for my August boxes, I'm subscribed to 
three boxes, and I check to see where my boxes are. Tracking info says 
they've been delivered, they shipped them to the old address though.

Obviously I'm pretty disappointed so I email them letting them know what 
happened. They respond saying that I should have emailed them to change my 
shipping address and that if I want my August boxes I will have to pay $6 
more per box for them to be shipped to the correct address, the address 
that I had already changed on their website which says NOTHING anywhere as 
far as having to email them to change your shipping location. 

I let them know that I thought it was pretty messed up how they were 
handling this situation considering it was their error and their website 
issues that caused it to happen. To which they let me know that they would 
be adding a note to their website to email them if you need to change your 
shipping address. Yet are still requiring that I pay them another $18 on 
top of the already $70+ that I paid for my August boxes. 

Now they've stopped responding to me and are censoring me from their 
Facebook page. 

This is a terrible company with terrible standards, they will not last 
long.﻿

column3:
Here is an email that was sent to me by Vega:
The ingredients in Vega\xae products are sourced primarily from North America 
and Europe. We choose to source some ingredients from their native climate; 
for example, we get our maca and SaviSeeds from Peru, and we get our 
chlorella from Japan. Vega\xae manufacturing and packaging facilities are in 
the United States and Canada. As I mentioned in my original email our pea 
and hemp protein is sourced from North America and our brown rice protein 
is sourced from China.﻿

column3:
Here is an email that was sent to me by Healthforce who creates 
Warriorforce:
Our brown rice in our Purity Protein and Warrior Food is sourced from 
Vietnam but it does originate in China. We have struggled with this for 
quite some time to try to satisfy our customers worries about Chinese 
ingredients but in the end the cleanest source of rice we can find is from 
China.
I hope this answers your question. If you need anything else, please reply 
or call us at 800-357-2717 Monday-Friday 9am-5pm MST.﻿

column3:
Its not exactly how much you eat, its what you are eating. No processed 
foods or boxed foods. No chemical crap. I don't eat sandwich meats, store 
bought bread (make my own with no sodium aluminum phosphate) no cow's milk 
(almond or soy instead), hotdogs, or basically anything that has added 
chemicals, preservatives, or or flavor enhancers, that stuff will slowly 
kill you. My taste has changed so much that I can't even drink the diet 
juice without diluting it with water. I am very careful what I put in my 
body now. Always read the ingredients. Do some research. If you don't the 
ingredients listed are, then you probably don't need to be eating it. We 
normally only eat out once a week at a restaurant. Drink mostly filtered 
water. Its the essence of life, you know.﻿

column3:
I can tolerate taste, it's just important to me that my meal replacement 
supplement is as close to the natural state of food as possible, and the 
only company that does that right now is GOL (although there's a higher 
ratio of sprouts to greens with their meal replacement). 

I would also, heavily, not recommend that you mix these with water - better 
if you can, obviously, but just mixing it with a non-dairy beverage gets 
the trick done.

Take it from a 26-year-old male who gets mistaken for an 18-year-old - 
these replacement meals (only vegan and whole food based) will provide you 
with the highest amounts of antioxidants.

﻿

to Walmart, a store I normally don't support, like you, and bought this. 
Your review states that OmniHealth's second ingredient is Fructose... So is 
Shakeology's! Shakeology lists their proprietary superfoods separately from 
its "other ingredients" but the first "other ingredient" in Shakeology is 
in fact Fructose. Also, you talk about the "fair value" of Shakeology 
compared to OmniHealth but what you fail to mention us that Shakeology is a 
MLM product. When a coach sells it, they get $32, not to mention the up 
line dollar amounts being given to the coach's coach. When you take away 
the MLM value of Shakeology, it actually comes out to just about the

You're an unethical coach doing a review on a product to keep your pockets

column3:
Congrats on your weight loss. I really love the concept of a truly plant 
based vegan diet. It is so good for the body, good for the environment and 
something I am currently striving for. I would just like to say, I think 
you looked beautiful before, just as you look beautiful after. I think that 
the concept of losing weight for health and for beauty need to be 
separated. We must be inclusive of all body types and people because 
honestly, you really didnt look "fat" before. Watching you call yourself 
disgusting I think is hurtful to yourself as well as anyone else watching 
that may be that size or perhaps even larger. Also, the correlation between 
"size zero and perfect" is also in my opinion, misleading. If you are happy 
where you are, that is perfect. I hope no one perceives a size six, or size 
16 for that matter as imperfect. A person of any size is valuable, 
beautiful, and perfect the way they are. If they choose to be healthy and 
loose weight, that awesome, but they are certainly not disgusting for being 
what society deems as overweight. I love everything else and dont mean to 
criticize, but as a plus size woman, just recently joining the quest to 
loose weight in a healthy, plant based way, I feel it is important that 
women accept and love themselves no matter what. I love my body and am not 
ashamed of it. I merely want to extend my health and longevity as much as 
possible and feel more energetic during my life. Thank you for this video 
:)﻿

column3:
Good for you I'm very proud of you and I know the commitment it takes to 
lose the weight! !
When I finally got fed up looking the way I did I've lost 132 pounds in 18 
months. It's the first time I've made an attempt to lose the weight the 
right way instead of Nutra Systems, Dr Bernstein or some other fad diet. 
Believe me I lost the weight on these programs. Biggest loss was my last 
one on Dr Bernstein 80 pounds 4 months.
Problem is I gained it all back and then some as soon as I started eating 
normal food.
When I decided to lose weight this time all I did was the simplest thing 
quit pop and junk food!! Very important to get off that shit!! At supper 
rather than fill up a dinner plate I used the next size of plate down!! I 
continued this at each of my meals.
I still ate what everybody else ate.
When I was finished and if I was still hungry I waited 20 minutes from when 
I finished eating and if I was still hungry I would have a little more. 
Honestly I rarely had more because i was comfortable.
If there was dessert like pie which I love I would just take half of 
whatever I used to. 
Never once stopped me from losing weight that week.
I stuck to this simple plan for a year. I chose to quit salt and drink 6 to 
8 bottles 500 ml water a day 
Ive kept the weight off for over a year and I feel a heck of a lot better 
and people look at me differently which is always good.
please remember I did this for me no else. I wanted to do what ever I could 
see my kids grow up and their kids.
After 3 months of no salt I went to Wendy's and got a classic single 
burger. I was so looking forward go that burger and it was a treat for me.
My mouth was watering and I took a bite and was shocked at the amount of 
salt in that burger.
It was like someone had put the whole thing of salt in that burger.
Well its been almost two years and I've never ordered a fast food burger 
since.
It's all about COMMITMENT and DETERMINATION which you seem to have both.
Congratulations on your significant weight loss you should be very proud of 
yourself!!﻿

column3:
@Pelonetillo Well depending on the type of sugar alcohols, they can indeed 
convert to glucose in the body. Some like erythritol are roughly 1/16th 
covertible to glucose. Others like maltitol are 50% convertible to glucose 
in the blood, and are 3 Calories per gram. Sorbitol is in the middle with 
2Calories per gram. Rather than half to calculate the convertability, it is 
easiest for me to avoid them or count them entirely.﻿

column3:
Good food, video, Doctor Dave. People making shakes at home can see how to 
perk up the pizzazz, to a cold shake for the folks on a diet. I use the 
Aspartame found in Equate from Walmart, to sweeten my coffee.

I use to use canned milk in my coffee, but your friend the HOSS IT IS had a 
video about Gossner boxed milk, available at the Dollar-Tree for $1 a 
quart. The Walmart down the road, had the Gossner milk for something like 
$2++ for a while.

Gossner milk can be stored on a kitchen shelf, with an expiration date of 1 
year later, typically. The milk is packaged with different fat contents. 
The milk doesn't need refrigeration until the package is opened.


Dollar Tree has a program, where someone can order a case of 12 quarters, 
and then pick them up at the Dollar Tree Store. The Gossner milk is made in 
the USA. Dollar Tree stores sell a lot of things made in China, even some 
of the ~food items. 

I looked online; there's a Dollar Tree in Crossville TN. Your Dollar Tree 
might NOT carry the milk in the store inventory, but it can be ordered and 
shipped to the store, for you. (This is assuming Doctor Dave is drinking 
milk, in his coffee. I didn't see a goat milk producer in the new videos.)﻿
